 continuity would improve? Maybe I would be a better artist? What's the general consensus here? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uwithroo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Withroo</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_purplespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/22/02 4:18:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3436.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.boomspeed.com/withroo/hisoka5.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: CIRCLES AND CONES... your opinion please!</span><hr size=1> Well, for me, I use basic shapes to get the general idea of proportion, and from there, I wing it, tweaking anything that doesn't look right.<br><br>It's all the matter of preference. Some can draw freehand any random shape and make them look good, while others prefer to use basic shapes to get the basic 'feel', like testing poses and whatnot.<br><br>Tutorials can only take you so far, and it's best you find what's good for yourself, and not really heed what everyone else is doing. Though, taking into consideration other factors (say, time, for instance) is important as well, since you may need to adjust certain things.<br><br>Try different styles and methods of drawing, and find what's best suited to you (comparing old drawings to newer ones help). Your style will always change, though detecting those changes can sometimes be a bit difficult. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><center><hr width=50%><br><br><table width="240" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><img src="http://www.boomspeed.com/withroo/mokona1.gif" alt="Puu!"></td><td><p align=left><font color="FFCCCC" size="-1"><small>I am cute.<br><br>Give me a <a href="http://pub58.ezboard.com/bthewartowerthefortrestofdoom">cookie</a>,<br><br>And feed my <a href="http://www.livejournal.com/~jezebel_complex">ego</a>.</font></td></tr></table></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/usexylyon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>sexylyon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/22/02 5:27:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3436.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: CIRCLES AND CONES... your opinion please!</span><hr size=1> hmm, i have no formal training either but i definitely noticed the improvement once i started using circles to define basic human shapes. i normally draw the basic head shape, and then work out the proportions of the rest of the body based on that first circle (foreshortening and whatnot aside).<br><br>its also very easy to work a cone-and-line sketch in a couple of seconds, and you can tell in an instant if you like the pose or it needs work. easy to fix a few lines and adjust proportions when its basically a stick figure, as opposed to trying to draw the thing &quot;fully fleshed&quot; and THEN finding out you put the knees too low or the shoulders too high or whatever.<br><br>i really suggest giving it a try and seeing if it works for you. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uretrotorque.showPublicProfile?language=EN>RetroTorque</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/22/02 9:14:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3436.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/sig.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: CIRCLES AND CONES... your opinion please!</span><hr size=1> Go with what works for you. I draw in loose, arbitrary, organic shapes, not set circles and cones. I find that drawing stick figures and ball/cones restricting, yet there are also those who draw who wouldn't draw like I do because they may find it restrictive. <p>Be well, do good work, and keep in touch. -Writer's Almanac NPR</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/utrekkieb47.showPublicProfile?language=EN>trekkieb47</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/22/02 10:42:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3436.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: CIRCLES AND CONES... your opinion please!</span><hr size=1> I typically use whatever I feel like at the time of my drawing. I agree with the above posters. If something works for your stick with it. But also apply rules of anatomy that you learn and see everyday.<br><br>For me i build up a very basic stick figure. Sometimes I go straight in and organically shape it like clay (even though its pencil ^_^)<br><br>Good luck, and PRACTICE PRACTICE PRACTICE<br><br>Berry <p>"Let's make sure history never forgets the name...Enterprise" - Captain Picard "Yesterday's Enterprise"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=iambob>I am bOb</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://liquid2k.com/iambob/cow.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/23/02 3:31:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3436.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.liquid2k.com/iambob/Shoroder.GIF height=100 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: CIRCLES AND CONES... your opinion please!</span><hr size=1> I do stick figures,but no ball and cone and cone thing. <p>Stand up straight...I look through the haze...I begin to walk...Through the maze...</p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showPrevMessage?topicID=3436.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showNextMessage?topicID=3436.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3436.topic&index=5><img src=http://www.polykarbon.com/bbsimage/addreply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.emailToFriend?topicID=3436.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.threadControl?topicID=3436.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/professional/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=3436.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=3436.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="r